  "chunk_index": 15,
  "summary": "Inspector Sharp continues his investigation into the death of Celia Austin by questioning Leonard Bateson and Valerie Hobhouse. During his interrogation of Bateson, Sharp explores whether Celia’s recent thefts were a calculated attempt to gain the attention of Colin McNaughton, who is obsessed with psychological abnormalities. Bateson denies having any psychological expertise that could have influenced Celia's behavior. Regarding the green ink spilled on Elizabeth Johnston's paper, Bateson suggests Nigel Chapman might be responsible because Nigel holds grudges and may have been provoked by Elizabeth's habit of correcting others. Bateson also notes that both Colin McNaughton and Gene Thompson have been annoyed by Elizabeth.\n\nSharp then interviews Valerie Hobhouse, a long-term resident of the dormitory, who describes Celia as a likable but unintelligent girl. Valerie expresses suspicion toward Silvia, noting that Silvia appeared self-satisfied when Sally Finch's shoe went missing, an incident that disrupted Sally's party plans. Regarding the destruction of Elizabeth's thesis, Valerie suggests that Patricia Lane might be responsible; she explains that Patricia is protective of her love interest, Nigel Chapman, and might act impulsively to defend him from suspicion. Valerie also posits that someone may be attempting to frame Nigel. Finally, discussing the method of Celia's death, Valerie suggests the morphine could have been placed in Celia's coffee while it was cooling, though she notes that using powder instead of a pill would make the act more difficult to execute without being noticed.",
